<DOC><DOCNO> WSJ880413-0114 </DOCNO><HL> New World Bank Agency For Investments Sets Debut </HL><SO> </SO><CO> FORGN EUROP </CO><IN> BNK MON </IN><G> EXE </G><DATELINE> WASHINGTON  </DATELINE><TEXT>   The World Bank said its agency that guarantees investments by industrial countries against political risk in the Third World will start operations this summer.    The Multilateral Investment Guarantee Agency, whose establishment was agreed on four years ago to encourage foreign investment in the Third World, will protect investors against such noncommercial risks as expropriation of assets, war and civil disturbances.    With commercial banks showing increasing reluctance to make new loans to debtor nations, Western governments believe foreign investment is the key to stimulating growth there. The World Bank said it now has enough subscriptions to the investment-guarantee agency's capital to allow it to start functioning.    Yesterday, the Reagan administration announced it would contribute about $200 million while Britain promised $50 million, bringing total pledges to $578 million. </TEXT></DOC>